It found that up to $1 billion awarded by the U.S. Department of Education Charter Schools Program—in more than 1,000 grants—was wasted on charter schools that never opened or opened for only brief periods before being shut down for mismanagement, poor performance, lack of enrollment, and fraud.
Two Delaware charter schools were started by the same management firm that won multi-year grants two years apart from each other.
A state commission imposed a range of academic sanctions on thirteen of the twenty-five charter schools up for renewal in the state.
Many of the problems we documented owe to the slipshod process the Charter Schools Program uses to review grant applications.
What’s needed instead is a moratorium on any new grants coming from the federal Charter Schools Program and a thorough audit of money that has been spent.